Where do I find Chase bank routing number?
You'll find your routing number and full account number by choosing your account tile and clicking the last 4 digits of the account name. You can also choose "Account details" from the "Things you can do" menu and then choose "See your account & routing number."

You can also find the routing number for your checking account at the bottom of each check (usually between your account number and the check number).

    Learn more about QuickPay: opens dialog

    Chase QuickPay is better together with ZelleSM

    Chase QuickPay with Zelle is a fast, easy and convenient way to send and receive money from your friends, no matter where they bank.

    What if my friends don't bank with Chase?
    No problem. Non-Chase customers can sign up with their bank's person-to-person payment service or visit zellepay.com for more options. In addition to Chase, Zelle members include major U.S. banks such as Bank of America, Wells Fargo and U.S. Bank. Visit zellepay.com to learn more.

    When will my money get there?
    • If your recipient is another Chase customer or their bank is a Zelle member and supports real-time payments, they'll typically get their money within minutes.
    • If your recipient's bank is a Zelle member but doesn't support real-time payments or your recipient is using clearXchange.com, they'll get their money 1 to 2 business days after it's sent, depending on their bank's processing time.
    • If your recipient is using the Zelle app to receive payments, they'll get their money soon after it's sent.

    How can we help you?

    I have questions about my Chase accounts.
    Send a secure message to our customer service specialists, and we'll follow up with personalized answers to your questions.
    I have feedback about chase.com.
    We're always working to make your online banking experience better. Tell us what you think of our site and how you think we could improve it.
    I have concerns or feedback about a Chase product or service.
    Understanding your concerns helps us improve. If you have a problem with a product or weren't satisfied with a Chase representative's service, please let us know. Did you have a great experience? We'd love to hear from you, too.

    Open information dialog: My accounts
    Close information dialog Begin information dialog
    Account value - This is the current value of your investment account.

    Adjustments - These are the additions to or subtractions from the amount funded.

    Amount due - The amount included in each payment represents the minimum amount due under your loan agreement. That amount may vary each month, so the amount for each payment may be different. You can also choose to pay another amount toward the principal and/or interest each month.

    Available balance - Your available balance is the portion of your "Present balance" that you can use right now. Pending transactions, such as check deposits, may not be available to use and wouldn't be included in your available balance.

    Change - This is the amount your account has changed today.

    Current balance - This may not include all transactions such as your most recent transactions, pending authorizations or interest that's accumulated since your last statement date.

    Interest saving balance - Pay this balance every month by your due date to avoid interest on new purchases and avoid prematurely paying off your flexible financing offer balances. Refer to your monthly statement for details. The amount here has been adjusted for payments, returned payments, credits and disputed amounts, but not interest or fees, incurred since your last statement.

    Last statement balance - This is your balance as of your last statement.

    Present balance - Your present balance is your balance at the end of the previous business day, plus or minus any transactions known to the bank that you've made today (e.g., deposits, debit card transactions, ATM withdrawals or payments scheduled for today). It doesn't include any checks you may have written but haven't yet been cashed.

    Total sales - This is your total sales amount for the period.
    End information dialog

    Total card sales: The total amount of your card sales transactions minus returns/refunds.

    Not processed: Card transactions that weren't processed. This could be due to a variety of reasons including a batch error. In most cases, we'll try to resolve any errors related to these transactions.

    Settled by AMEX/Discover: Transactions AMEX or Discover settle and fund.

    Settled by Chase: Transactions we settle and fund.

    Misc. adjustments: Other debits or credits that may not be transaction related. This might include charges for supplies/equipment or an adjustment to a payment brand fee.

    Disputes: Disputed or reversed transactions, which can happen if a customer refuses to accept responsibility for a card transaction.

    Fees: Fees or charges based on payment processing activity including payment brand fees and other fees we charge. We'll apply some fees monthly, which might result in a net withdrawal from your account if those fees are more than the amount of your card sales on a given day.

    Deposited amount: The net amount sent to your deposit account.
